==English==

===Etymology===
from [[turn]] + [[key]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# {{slang}} A [[warder]] or [[jailer]] / [[goaler]]; [[keeper]] of the [[key]]s in a [[prison]]
#*'''1836:''' Charles Dickens, ''[http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/ot2www-pubeng?specfile=/texts/english/modeng/publicsearch/modengpub.o2w&act=surround&offset=268726479&tag=Dickens,+Charles,+1812-1870:+The+Pickwick+papers,+1836&query=turnkey&id=DicPick The Pickwick papers]''
#*:...they passed through an open door into a lobby, from which a heavy gate, opposite to that by which they had entered, and which was guarded by a stout '''turnkey''' with the key in his hand, led at once into the interior of the prison.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}
# [[ready]] to use without further [[assembly]] or [[test]]; [[supplied]] in a [[state]] that is ready to [[turn on]] and [[operate]] (typically refers to an assembly that is [[outsource]]d for manufacture)
#:''They wanted a '''turnkey''' solution for the entire system, but we could only provide the enclosure.''

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}
# to supply a turnkey product; to supply something fully [[assemble]]d and ready to use
#:''We can sell you all the parts, or we can '''turnkey''' the entire unit.''

===Related terms===
*[[turn]]
*[[key]]

